    /**
     * Wizardry maze level binary record format used by {@link MazeLevelV1}
     * (Wizardry I–III style: Proving Grounds / Knight of Diamonds / Legacy /
     * etc).
     *
     * <p>
     * <b>Byte order:</b> all 16-bit values are little-endian signed shorts (see
     * {@code EndianUtils.readSwappedShort}).</p>
     *
     * <p>
     * <b>Coordinate conventions in this loader:</b> {@code row = x},
     * {@code column = y}. The cell-info index map is stored as
     * {@code cellInfoLocations[column][row]} (column-major).</p>
     *
     * <h2>Top-level layout (offsets from start of level buffer)</h2>
     * <pre>
     * 0x000..0x077  West walls/doors bitmap     (120 bytes)
     * 0x078..0x0EF  South walls/doors bitmap    (120 bytes)
     * 0x0F0..0x167  East walls/doors bitmap     (120 bytes)
     * 0x168..0x1DF  North walls/doors bitmap    (120 bytes)
     * 0x1E0..0x22F  Lair (monster) bitmap       ( 80 bytes)  [used by V1]
     * 0x230..0x2F7  CellInfo index map          (200 bytes)
     * 0x2F8..0x35F  CellInfo table (16 entries) (104 bytes)
     * 0x360..0x37D  Encounter odds (3 structs)  ( 30 bytes)
     * </pre>
     *
     * <h3>Walls/doors bitmaps (4 directional planes)</h3>
     * Each direction plane is {@code 6 bytes/column * 20 columns = 120 bytes}.
     * For a given cell (row, col):
     * <ul>
     * <li>{@code byteIndex = col * 6 + (row / 4)}</li>
     * <li>{@code bitPairShift = (row % 4) * 2}</li>
     * <li>2 bits encode that side: {@code bit0 = wall},
     * {@code bit1 = door}</li>
     * </ul>
     * The same scheme is repeated for each direction plane at base offsets:
     * {@code +0} (west), {@code +120} (south), {@code +240} (east),
     * {@code +360} (north).
     *
     * <p>
     * <b>Hidden doors:</b> this loader treats “wall=1 and door=1” on the same
     * side as a hidden door (and keeps both wall+door flags set).</p>
     *
     * <h3>Lair bitmap (wandering encounter spawn flags)</h3>
     * Stored as {@code 4 bytes/column * 20 columns = 80 bytes}, starting at
     * {@code 0x1E0}. For (row, col):
     * <ul>
     * <li>{@code byteIndex = col * 4 + (row / 8)}</li>
     * <li>{@code bit = (row % 8)} (LSB-first)</li>
     * </ul>
     * If the bit is 1, the cell is marked as a lair/spawn point by
     * {@link MazeLevelV1}.
     *
     * <h3>CellInfo index map (“sqrextra”)</h3>
     * Stored column-major starting at {@code 0x230}. There are
     * {@code 10 bytes/column} (because rows are packed two per byte):
     * <ul>
     * <li>Low nibble (bits 0..3): index for even row</li>
     * <li>High nibble (bits 4..7): index for the next odd row</li>
     * </ul>
     * Each nibble is a 0..15 index into the CellInfo table described below.
     *
     * <h3>CellInfo table (16 entries)</h3>
     * Begins at {@code 0x2F8} and is logically:
     * <ul>
     * <li><b>Types:</b> 8 bytes of packed nibbles at {@code 0x2F8..0x2FF}.
     * Entry {@code i} uses low nibble if {@code i} even, else high nibble.</li>
     * <li><b>val0:</b> 16 little-endian int16 values at
     * {@code 0x300 + i*2}</li>
     * <li><b>val1:</b> 16 little-endian int16 values at
     * {@code 0x320 + i*2}</li>
     * <li><b>val2:</b> 16 little-endian int16 values at
     * {@code 0x340 + i*2}</li>
     * </ul>
     *
     * <p>
     * Type codes are {@link CellType} ordinal values (0..15). The V1 loader
     * interprets the (val0,val1,val2) triple by type, for example:</p>
     * <ul>
     * <li>{@code STAIRS}/{@code CHUTE}/{@code TELEPORT}: destination = (val0
     * level, val1 row, val2 col)</li>
     * <li>{@code PIT}: damage dice = (val0, val1, val2)</li>
     * <li>{@code DAMAGE}: damage dice = (val1, val2, val0)</li>
     * <li>{@code ELEVATOR}: elevatorTo=val1, elevatorFrom=val2</li>
     * <li>{@code ENCOUNTER}: encounterId=val2, occurrences=val0 (and forces
     * chest=true)</li>
     * <li>{@code MESSAGE}: val2 acts as a “subcode” and further specializes
     * meaning of val0/val1/val2</li>
     * </ul>
     *
     * <h3>Encounter odds (3 structs)</h3>
     * Begins at {@code 0x360}. Three consecutive 10-byte structs:
     * <pre>
     * int16 minEnemy;
     * int16 extraRangeOffset;
     * int16 totExtraRanges;
     * int16 rangeSize;
     * int16 extraRangeOdds; // percent chance (0..100) to advance to the next range
     * </pre>
     */
