    /**
     * Wizardry maze level binary record format used by {@link MazeLevelV4}
     * (Wizardry IV: Return of Werdna).
     *
     * <p>
     * <b>Byte order:</b> all 16-bit values are little-endian signed shorts (see
     * {@code EndianUtils.readSwappedShort}).</p>
     *
     * <p>
     * <b>Dimension:</b> this loader assumes a fixed 20x20 grid.</p>
     *
     * <h2>Top-level layout (offsets from start of level buffer)</h2>
     * <pre>
     * 0x000..0x077  West walls/doors bitmap     (120 bytes)
     * 0x078..0x0EF  South walls/doors bitmap    (120 bytes)
     * 0x0F0..0x167  East walls/doors bitmap     (120 bytes)
     * 0x168..0x1DF  North walls/doors bitmap    (120 bytes)
     * 0x1E0..0x22F  (unused by this loader)     ( 80 bytes)  [present in data, not interpreted here]
     * 0x230..0x2F7  CellInfo index map          (200 bytes)
     * 0x2F8..0x35F  CellInfo table (16 entries) (104 bytes)
     * 0x360..0x37D  Encounter odds (3 structs)  ( 30 bytes)
     * </pre>
     *
     * <h3>Walls/doors bitmaps</h3>
     * Identical packing to {@link MazeLevelV1}:
     * {@code byteIndex = col*6 + row/4}, {@code shift=(row%4)*2}, then
     * {@code bit0=wall, bit1=door} for that side.
     *
     * <p>
     * <b>Hidden doors:</b> “wall=1 and door=1” on the same side is treated as a
     * hidden door.</p>
     *
     * <h3>CellInfo index map and CellInfo table</h3>
     * Identical structure and offsets to {@link MazeLevelV1}:
     * <ul>
     * <li>{@code 0x230}: 200-byte column-major nibble map (two rows per byte,
     * 0..15 indices)</li>
     * <li>{@code 0x2F8}: 16-entry CellInfo definition table (type nibble + 3
     * int16 parameters)</li>
     * </ul>
     *
     * <p>
     * Type codes are {@link CellType} ordinals (0..15). The V4 loader uses the
     * same underlying (type,val0,val1,val2) representation, but interprets
     * several types with Werdna-specific rules, e.g.:</p>
     * <ul>
     * <li>{@code SPINNER}: may be a plain spinner, or a rotator. A “rotator” is
     * detected by {@code val0==-1} and {@code val2 in {0,1}}, with rotation
     * direction taken from {@code val1}.</li>
     * <li>{@code ELEVATOR}: destination level is {@code val1}, destination
     * row/col remain the current cell, and {@code elevatorFrom=val2}.</li>
     * <li>{@code ENCOUNTER}: encounterId = {@code val2} (no “occurrences” field
     * used here).</li>
     * <li>{@code MESSAGE}: heavily overloaded in Werdna; values can encode
     * message display, item gating, encounter triggers, riddle-answer tables,
     * and summoning-circle markers (often via special/negative codes).</li>
     * </ul>
     *
     * <h3>Encounter odds (3 structs)</h3>
     * Same 3x10-byte {@code EncounterOdds} structs at {@code 0x360} as V1:
     * <pre>
     * int16 minEnemy;
     * int16 extraRangeOffset;
     * int16 totExtraRanges;
     * int16 rangeSize;
     * int16 extraRangeOdds;
     * </pre>
     */
